Linux Sudo Lab – Beginner Exercise
Objective

Understand what sudo does

Learn when and how to use it safely

Practice running commands as a superuser

Step 1 — Check your current user
whoami

Output example: nambia-mangare

This shows you’re a normal user.

Step 2 — List a root-only directory
ls /root

Likely: Permission denied

This shows that normal users cannot access root directories without sudo.

Step 3 — Try with sudo
sudo ls /root

You will be prompted for your password

After entering it correctly, you’ll see the contents.

Lesson: sudo lets you temporarily act as root.

Step 4 — Check sudo privileges
sudo -l

Lists what commands you are allowed to run as root

Helps you understand your permissions

Step 5 — Safe root command practice

Create a folder in a root-only location:

sudo mkdir /tmp/test_sudo_lab

Check it:

ls -l /tmp | grep test_sudo_lab

Remove it:

sudo rmdir /tmp/test_sudo_lab

Lesson: You can practice safely in /tmp without harming your system.

Step 6 — Running the last command with sudo

If you forget sudo for a command:

apt update       # run normally → may fail
sudo !!          # reruns previous command as root
